WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.700 --> 00:00:04.000
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:19.370 --> 00:00:24.480
&gt;&gt; Okay. Well, good afternoon
and thank you all for coming.

00:00:24.480 --> 00:00:26.050
I'm Mary-Jane Deeb.

00:00:26.050 --> 00:00:28.760
I'm the Chief of the
African Middle East Division

00:00:28.760 --> 00:00:31.770
and I'm delighted to
see you all here.

00:00:31.770 --> 00:00:33.520
And so welcome.

00:00:33.520 --> 00:00:34.820
Some of you are new.

00:00:34.820 --> 00:00:39.150
Some of you have been
here many times before.

00:00:39.150 --> 00:00:45.580 position:56%
So before we start the program, let
me say something about our division.

00:00:45.580 --> 00:00:55.460 position:56%
We are the African and Middle East
Division and we include 78 countries

00:00:55.460 --> 00:00:57.610
in terms of our responsibility.

00:00:57.610 --> 00:01:03.910
Those 78 countries are about
the whole African continent,

00:01:03.910 --> 00:01:06.810
North and Sub-Sahara and Africa.

00:01:06.810 --> 00:01:12.550
We have the whole Middle
East that extends to --

00:01:12.550 --> 00:01:15.950
from Morocco to Afghanistan.

00:01:15.950 --> 00:01:19.290
We also include the
Near East section,

00:01:19.290 --> 00:01:25.190
Central Asia, Armenia and Georgia.

00:01:25.190 --> 00:01:31.700
And we have the Hebraic section
which also includes collections

00:01:31.700 --> 00:01:36.430
that come from all over the
world to the collections.

00:01:36.430 --> 00:01:44.490
Now the collections that
we are custodian of are

00:01:44.490 --> 00:01:48.320 position:56%
in the languages of those countries.

00:01:48.320 --> 00:01:53.230
In other words, if you're
doing research on let's say,

00:01:53.230 --> 00:01:59.200
today's topic on Lebanon, if you
were looking for sources in Arabic,

00:01:59.200 --> 00:02:01.660
they would be part of
our collections here.

00:02:01.660 --> 00:02:08.920 position:56%
But if those sources on Lebanon were
in English, or French, or German,

00:02:08.920 --> 00:02:13.700
or Greek or Italian, they would
be part of the general collection.

00:02:13.700 --> 00:02:16.870
In other words, we
collect in the vernacular

00:02:16.870 --> 00:02:21.030
and in the scripts
of those countries.

00:02:21.030 --> 00:02:26.000
Our programs include --

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:31.930
so we collect and we serve
these materials to the audience.

00:02:31.930 --> 00:02:37.220
But we also do exhibits and
we've had some major exhibits

00:02:37.220 --> 00:02:40.120
in the past five years
on Afghanistan.

00:02:40.120 --> 00:02:43.660
We've had one on the Hebrew book.

00:02:43.660 --> 00:02:45.870
We had one on the Persian book.

00:02:45.870 --> 00:02:48.640
We had one of the Armenian book.

00:02:48.640 --> 00:02:54.360
And we're possibly trying now
to raise funds and have one

00:02:54.360 --> 00:02:58.260
of the Arabic book and
on the African book.

00:02:58.260 --> 00:03:05.710
We also have symposia and we bring
scholars from all over the world

00:03:05.710 --> 00:03:09.310
to discuss various topics.

00:03:09.310 --> 00:03:16.130
We just had two recently, one on
the ancient city of Tyre in Lebanon

00:03:16.130 --> 00:03:21.810
and we had international
archaeologists, museum keepers,

00:03:21.810 --> 00:03:28.170
curators, artists and
others come and participate.

00:03:28.170 --> 00:03:38.030
And we had a Juneteenth symposium,
conference on the end of slavery

00:03:38.030 --> 00:03:43.890
and again, it was -- we had
packed audiences in both cases.

00:03:43.890 --> 00:03:46.660
So why are we all, why
are we doing these things?

00:03:46.660 --> 00:03:52.340
We're doing this in order to
make our collections come alive.

00:03:52.340 --> 00:03:55.240
We collect books and
we take care of them.

00:03:55.240 --> 00:03:56.540
We preserve them.

00:03:56.540 --> 00:03:57.840
We store them.

00:03:57.840 --> 00:03:59.430
We serve them.

00:03:59.430 --> 00:04:04.550
But we also want people to
understand how those cultures

00:04:04.550 --> 00:04:09.110
and those societies
live, how they speak,

00:04:09.110 --> 00:04:12.910
how they vote, how they write.

00:04:12.910 --> 00:04:18.750
And it is through these programs,
through the scholars who come

00:04:18.750 --> 00:04:23.220
and share with us the work they
have done, through film producers

00:04:23.220 --> 00:04:27.810
as we have today, that we
make these cultures live.

00:04:27.810 --> 00:04:31.410
Live in your imaginations,
in your thoughts.

00:04:31.410 --> 00:04:38.670
We just had a wonderful program on
Ethiopia with someone who had gone

00:04:38.670 --> 00:04:43.350
to Ethiopia and had filmed
and taken photographs

00:04:43.350 --> 00:04:49.830
of the beautiful topography
of Ethiopia,

00:04:49.830 --> 00:04:53.290
the mountains, the
lakes, the fields.

00:04:53.290 --> 00:04:59.380
So in this way, those of us who are
lucky enough to be present, live --

00:04:59.380 --> 00:05:07.090
leave this one-hour presentation
enriched and more knowledgeable

00:05:07.090 --> 00:05:10.630
than when they first
came to the Library.

00:05:10.630 --> 00:05:14.420
We are also addressing people
outside of the Library,

00:05:14.420 --> 00:05:19.250
across the world because since
we are webcasting our programs,

00:05:19.250 --> 00:05:22.580
people from every continent
in the world can have access

00:05:22.580 --> 00:05:25.450
to these programs and
see them and learn

00:05:25.450 --> 00:05:28.720
about the programs we're doing.

00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:35.720
So now, I would like to introduce
